\subsection{The [[list]] command}
\label{sec:list-command}

The [[list]] command gives a compact overview of the development
log, one line per commit---like [[git log --oneline]] but showing
the start time and command instead of the commit message subject.
This is useful for quickly finding a session to inspect with
[[play]], or for checking what a student has been working on.

When a commit contains multiple runs (because the student ran the
same code several times without editing), we show the first run's
details and append [[(N runs)]] so the teacher knows there is more
to explore.

<<typer commands>>=
@app.command(name="list")
def list_commits(
    source: Annotated[
        Optional[str],
        typer.Argument(
            help=(
                "Source: directory with .learnlog/ "
                "or a .bundle file. "
                "Defaults to current directory."
            ),
        ),
    ] = None,
    show_all: Annotated[
        bool,
        typer.Option(
            "--all", "-a",
            help=(
                "Include learnlog's own runs in the "
                "output."
            ),
        ),
    ] = False,
):
    """List commits with start time and command."""
    import shutil

    repo, tmpdir = resolve_source(source)
    try:
        commits = get_commits(repo)
        if not commits:
            raise SystemExit("No commits found.")

        filter_lr = not show_all
        for commit in commits:
            <<get and summarise commit>>
    finally:
        if tmpdir is not None:
            shutil.rmtree(tmpdir, ignore_errors=True)
@

For each commit we fetch the full message body, optionally filter
out learnlog's own runs using [[filter_learnlog_runs]], and then
extract the summary with [[parse_run_summary]].
Commits whose runs are all filtered out (or that have no run
blocks, like the initial commit) are silently skipped.

<<get and summarise commit>>=
body = repo.git(
    "log", "-1", "--format=%B", commit["hash"],
).stdout.rstrip("\n")
if filter_lr:
    body = filter_learnlog_runs(body)
summary = parse_run_summary(body)
if summary is None:
    continue
command, start_time, run_count = summary
short_hash = commit["hash"][:7]
suffix = (
    f" ({run_count} runs)" if run_count > 1 else ""
)
typer.echo(
    f"{short_hash} {start_time} {command}{suffix}"
)
@

Let's verify that the command lists commits with the expected
format:

