\subsection{The [[push]] command}
\label{sec:push}

The [[push]] command sends all branches to [[origin]] with tracking
([[--all -u]]).
The expected workflow is that the remote repository starts empty, so
a regular push suffices.
For the less common case where the remote already contains commits
(\eg a GitLab repository initialised with a README), the optional
[[--force]] / [[-f]] flag overrides the remote's history.
This is safe because [[.learnlog/]] is a single-writer recording
artefact---there is no risk of overwriting someone else's work.

Unlike [[repo.git()]], which captures output with a ten-second
timeout, [[push]] uses [[subprocess.run]] with inherited standard
I/O---the same approach as the [[git]] passthrough command
(\cref{sec:git}).
This lets the user see transfer progress and respond to credential
prompts.

<<typer commands>>=
@app.command()
def push(
    force: Annotated[
        bool,
        typer.Option(
            "--force", "-f",
            help=(
                "Force-push, overwriting remote history. "
                "Useful when the remote was initialised "
                "with its own commits."
            ),
        ),
    ] = False,
    directory: Annotated[
        Optional[pathlib.Path],
        typer.Option(
            "--dir", "-C",
            help="Directory containing .learnlog/.",
        ),
    ] = None,
):
    """Push the learnlog repository to its remote."""
    workdir = resolve_workdir(directory)
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)

    cmd = ["git", "push", "--all", "-u"]
    if force:
        cmd.append("--force")
    cmd.append("origin")

    result = subprocess.run(
        cmd,
        env=repo.env,
        cwd=str(repo.workdir),
    )
    raise typer.Exit(code=result.returncode)
@

We test [[push]] by creating a bare repository as the remote target,
configuring [[origin]] to point at it, and verifying that the commits
arrive:

<<test functions>>=
def test_push_command(workdir, monkeypatch):
    """Push sends commits to a bare remote."""
    from learnlog.cli import app
    from typer.testing import CliRunner
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    bare = workdir.parent / "remote.git"
    subprocess.run(
        ["git", "init", "--bare", str(bare)],
        capture_output=True, check=True,
    )
    monkeypatch.chdir(workdir)
    runner = CliRunner()
    runner.invoke(
        app, ["set-remote", str(bare)]
    )
    result = runner.invoke(app, ["push"])
    assert result.exit_code == 0
    log = subprocess.run(
        ["git", "--git-dir", str(bare),
         "log", "--oneline"],
        capture_output=True, text=True,
    )
    assert log.returncode == 0
    assert "learnlog" in log.stdout

def test_push_to_divergent_remote(workdir, monkeypatch):
    """Force-push works when remote has divergent history."""
    from learnlog.cli import app
    from typer.testing import CliRunner
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)
    # Simulate a GitLab repo initialised with a README:
    # create a helper repo with a commit, then clone it
    # as a bare repo to serve as the remote.
    helper = workdir.parent / "helper"
    helper.mkdir()
    subprocess.run(
        ["git", "init", str(helper)],
        capture_output=True, check=True,
    )
    subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", str(helper),
         "config", "commit.gpgsign", "false"],
        capture_output=True, check=True,
    )
    (helper / "README.md").write_text("# Project\n")
    subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", str(helper), "add", "."],
        capture_output=True, check=True,
    )
    subprocess.run(
        ["git", "-C", str(helper),
         "commit", "-m", "Initial commit"],
        capture_output=True, check=True,
        env={**os.environ,
             "GIT_AUTHOR_NAME": "Test",
             "GIT_AUTHOR_EMAIL": "test@test",
             "GIT_COMMITTER_NAME": "Test",
             "GIT_COMMITTER_EMAIL": "test@test"},
    )
    bare = workdir.parent / "divergent-remote.git"
    subprocess.run(
        ["git", "clone", "--bare",
         str(helper), str(bare)],
        capture_output=True, check=True,
    )
    monkeypatch.chdir(workdir)
    runner = CliRunner()
    runner.invoke(
        app, ["set-remote", str(bare)]
    )
    # Without --force, divergent history is rejected.
