\subsection{The [[pull]] command}
\label{sec:pull}

The [[pull]] command is the receiving counterpart to [[push]]: it
fetches new commits from [[origin]] and updates the local branches.
Where [[push]] uses [[git push --all -u]], [[pull]] uses
[[git pull --all]] to mirror the operation in the other direction.

Merge conflicts are not a practical concern because [[.learnlog/]]
is a single-writer recording artefact---the same assumption that
makes [[--force]] safe on [[push]].

Like [[push]] and [[clone]], we use inherited I/O for transfer
progress and credential prompts.

<<typer commands>>=
@app.command()
def pull(
    directory: Annotated[
        Optional[pathlib.Path],
        typer.Option(
            "--dir", "-C",
            help="Directory containing .learnlog/.",
        ),
    ] = None,
):
    """Pull new commits from the remote."""
    workdir = resolve_workdir(directory)
    repo = LearnlogRepo(workdir)

    result = subprocess.run(
        ["git", "pull", "--all"],
        env=repo.env,
        cwd=str(repo.workdir),
    )
    raise typer.Exit(code=result.returncode)
@

